english:
  title: Letter to the Official Wu Yue
  author: Lee Chang-yong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Spring's warmth brings comfort to your days—I humbly offer my prayers. The Marshal's府, with its magnanimous breadth and generous spirit, extends shelter and protection to our small realm. How can mere words capture the gratitude carved upon our hearts?

    Since our submission in the year Gimyo, when the commander Hecheng made his inspection tour, we have honored the custom: the tribute we present receives the Emperor's decree, whereby ten envoys from the Upper Kingdom come to receive and carry away our gifts—such is the unchanging protocol. Yet in recent times, a certain wave of chaos swept through the roads, and for years we could not maintain our customary offerings of local goods. When Sinmyo arrived and the great armies of the Upper Kingdom approached our borders, my elder brother, the Duke of Huai'an, came before the generals to reaffirm our bonds of friendship, pledging eternal service and devotion. From that time forward, we have repeatedly sent treasures and tributes to the Imperial seat. In the twelfth month of Musu, we dispatched Kim Bodong and Song Eongi. In the sixth month of Gihai, we sent No Yeon and Kim Kyeom. And in the twelfth month of Gihai, we sent my younger brother, the Duke of Xinan, as our humble envoy to pay court to the Son of Heaven. Our heart of service has never wavered.

    Now that No Yeon has returned with your gracious message, I am deeply moved by your continued care and benevolence. Regarding the imperial emissaries and officials—that they lodge directly at our residence—our humble dwelling is too modest to receive them with proper honor, so we have established a separate residence in a finer location. This is done solely to show respect to the Imperial mandate; we harbor no other intention. I have now accepted your wise instruction and arranged for their reception at our own quarters.

    As for the matter of subjects under the Wan-hu's administration who have committed offenses and fled on horseback to our lands in the twelfth month of last year—since last year, no one from that country has fled here. Should anyone have escaped and arrived, being already guilty, they would surely know that the Upper Kingdom seeks them out. They would hide their traces in wilderness and empty places where no one dwells. How could we possibly search out and reveal those concealed in such desolation?

    I humbly beseech the Marshal to understand our circumstances, to extend your compassion further, and to allow us forever to serve with devoted strength. This would be our realm's greatest fortune. I have prepared our humble local products as listed in the attached record. I hope you will be pleased to accept them.
  footnotes:
    - Gimyo year refers to 1219 CE in the Mongol calendar system
    - The reference to the Upper Kingdom (상국) indicates the Mongol Yuan Dynasty
    - The Marshal's府 (수부) refers to the military administration through which this letter was directed
    - The title 'Official Wu Yue' likely refers to a Mongol or Yuan official overseeing relations with the Korean kingdom
